	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">tokumaru wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">...and allegedly why the NES has sprite 0 instead of a proper vcount interrupt.</div><br />They could still have offered something much better... Why not generate an IRQ when the hit happens?</div><br />Patented, if I recall correctly.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Why not allow more than 1 hit per frame?</div><br />You mean like CXCLR in the Atari 2600 TIA?<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Why require that 2 solid pixels collide?</div><br />A background pixel has to overlap a sprite pixel because such systems used for hardware collision detection were in the unpatented prior art in 1983. See the player/bg collision bits in the Atari 2600 TIA.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Not violating a patent should not be an excuse to offer a crippled feature...</div>
<br />Unless you don't want to get sued. Nintendo has since been sued by patent holders like Immersion (controller with built-in vibration) and Anascape (spring-loaded analog trigger with buckling feel at end of travel).

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


